{"nodes":[{"content":"Data binding in depth","pos":[78,99]},{"content":"Data binding is a way for your app's UI to display data, and optionally to stay in sync with that data.","pos":[113,216]},{"content":"Data binding in depth","pos":[223,244]},{"content":"Updated for UWP apps on Windows 10.","pos":[249,284]},{"content":"For Windows 8.x articles, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>archive<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132)</ept>","pos":[285,377]},{"content":"Important APIs","pos":[386,400]},{"content":"Binding class","pos":[412,425]},{"content":"DataContext","pos":[494,505]},{"content":"INotifyPropertyChanged","pos":[574,596]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  This topic describes data binding features in detail.","pos":[659,722]},{"content":"For a short, practical introduction, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Data binding overview<ept id=\"p1\">](data-binding-quickstart.md)</ept>.","pos":[723,816]},{"content":"Data binding is a way for your app's UI to display data, and optionally to stay in sync with that data.","pos":[821,924]},{"content":"Data binding allows you to separate the concern of data from the concern of UI, and that results in a simpler conceptual model as well as better readability, testability, and maintainability of your app.","pos":[925,1128]},{"content":"You can use data binding to simply display values from a data source when the UI is first shown, but not to respond to changes in those values.","pos":[1130,1273]},{"content":"This is called one-time binding, and it works well for data whose values don't change during run-time.","pos":[1274,1376]},{"content":"Additionally, you can choose to \"observe\" the values and to update the UI when they change.","pos":[1377,1468]},{"content":"This is called one-way binding, and it works well for read-only data.","pos":[1469,1538]},{"content":"Ultimately, you can choose to both observe and update, so that changes that the user makes to values in the UI are automatically pushed back into the data source.","pos":[1539,1701]},{"content":"This is called two-way binding, and it works well for read-write data.","pos":[1702,1772]},{"content":"Here are some examples.","pos":[1773,1796]},{"pos":[1802,1942],"content":"You could use one-time binding to bind an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Image<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242752)</ept> to the current user's photo."},{"pos":[1947,2132],"content":"You could use one-way binding to bind a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242878)</ept> to a collection of real-time news articles grouped by newspaper section."},{"pos":[2137,2280],"content":"You could use two-way binding to bind a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>TextBox<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR209683)</ept> to a customer's name in a form."},{"content":"There are two kinds of binding, and they're both typically declared in UI markup.","pos":[2282,2363]},{"content":"You can choose to use either the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>{x:Bind} markup extension<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204783)</ept> or the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>{Binding} markup extension<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204782)</ept>.","pos":[2364,2577]},{"content":"And you can even use a mixture of the two in the same app—even on the same UI element.","pos":[2578,2664]},{"content":"{x:Bind} is new for Windows 10 and it has better performance.","pos":[2665,2726]},{"content":"{Binding} has more features.","pos":[2727,2755]},{"content":"All the details described in this topic apply to both kinds of binding unless we explicitly say otherwise.","pos":[2756,2862]},{"content":"Sample apps that demonstrate {x:Bind}","pos":[2866,2903]},{"pos":[2911,2978],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>{x:Bind} sample<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619989)</ept>."},{"pos":[2983,3051],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>QuizGame<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/Microsoft/Windows-appsample-quizgame)</ept>."},{"pos":[3056,3129],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAML UI Basics sample<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619992)</ept>."},{"content":"Sample apps that demonstrate {Binding}","pos":[3133,3171]},{"pos":[3179,3256],"content":"Download the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Bookstore1<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=532950)</ept> app."},{"pos":[3261,3338],"content":"Download the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Bookstore2<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=532952)</ept> app."},{"content":"Every binding involves these pieces","pos":[3343,3378]},{"content":"A <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>binding source<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[3384,3403]},{"content":"This is the source of the data for the binding, and it can be an instance of any class that has members whose values you want to display in your UI.","pos":[3404,3552]},{"content":"A <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>binding target<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[3557,3576]},{"content":"This is a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DependencyProperty<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242362)</ept> of the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>FrameworkElement<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR208706)</ept> in your UI that displays the data.","pos":[3577,3792]},{"content":"A <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>binding object<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[3797,3816]},{"content":"This is the piece that transfers data values from the source to the target, and optionally from the target back to the source.","pos":[3817,3943]},{"content":"The binding object is created at XAML load time from your <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>{x:Bind}<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204783)</ept> or <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>{Binding}<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204782)</ept> markup extension.","pos":[3944,4161]},{"content":"In the following sections, we'll take a closer look at the binding source, the binding target, and the binding object.","pos":[4163,4281]},{"content":"And we'll link the sections together with the example of binding a button's content to a string property named <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>NextButtonText<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, which belongs to a class named <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HostViewModel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[4282,4462]},{"content":"Binding source","pos":[4468,4482]},{"content":"Here's a very rudimentary implementation of a class that we could use as a binding source.","pos":[4484,4574]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  If you're using <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>{Binding}<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204782)</ept> with Visual C++ component extensions (C++/CX) then you'll need to add the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>BindableAttribute<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Hh701872)</ept> attribute to your binding source class.","pos":[4576,4867]},{"content":"If you're using <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>{x:Bind}<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204783)</ept> then you don't need that attribute.","pos":[4868,4988]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Adding a details view<ept id=\"p1\">](data-binding-quickstart.md#adding-a-details-view)</ept> for a code snippet.","pos":[4989,5086]},{"content":"That implementation of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HostViewModel<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and its property <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>NextButtonText<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, are only appropriate for one-time binding.","pos":[5259,5380]},{"content":"But one-way and two-way bindings are extremely common, and in those kinds of binding the UI automatically updates in response to changes in the data values of the binding source.","pos":[5381,5559]},{"content":"In order for those kinds of binding to work correctly, you need to make your binding source \"observable\" to the binding object.","pos":[5560,5687]},{"content":"So in our example, if we want to one-way or two-way bind to the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>NextButtonText<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property, then any changes that happen at run-time to the value of that property need to be made observable to the binding object.","pos":[5688,5901]},{"content":"One way of doing that is to derive the class that represents your binding source from <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DependencyObject<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242356)</ept>, and expose a data value through a <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>DependencyProperty<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR242362)</ept>.","pos":[5903,6188]},{"content":"That's how a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>FrameworkElement<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/BR208706)</ept> becomes observable.","pos":[6189,6302]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>FrameworkElements<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> are good binding sources right out of the box.","pos":[6303,6371]},{"content":"A more lightweight way of making a class observable—and a necessary one for classes that already have a base class—is to implement <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>System.ComponentModel.INotifyPropertyChanged<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/system.componentmodel.inotifypropertychanged.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[6373,6659]},{"content":"This really just involves implementing a single event named <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>PropertyChanged<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[