inding source class from the class that represents our page of markup.","pos":[21502,21595]},{"content":"We do that by adding a property (of type <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HostViewModel<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> in this case) to our <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HostView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> page class.","pos":[21596,21700]},{"content":"That done, we can now take a closer look at the markup that declares the binding object.","pos":[22000,22088]},{"content":"The example below uses the same <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Button.Content<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> binding target we used in the \"Binding target\" section earlier, and shows it being bound to the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HostViewModel.NextButtonText<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> property.","pos":[22089,22278]},{"content":"Notice the value that we specify for <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Path<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[22427,22473]},{"content":"This value is interpreted in the context of the page itself, and in this case the path begins by referencing the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ViewModel<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property that we just added to the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HostView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> page.","pos":[22474,22654]},{"content":"That property returns a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HostViewModel<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> instance, and so we can dot into that object to access the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HostViewModel.NextButtonText<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> property.","pos":[22655,22798]},{"content":"And we specify <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Mode<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, to override the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>{x:Bind}<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/Mt204783)</ept> default of one-time.","pos":[22799,22929]},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Path<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.data.binding.path)</ept> property supports a variety of syntax options for binding to nested properties, attached properties, and integer and string 